# AST dispatch: exhaustive switch vs chained `ast.is`

When **dispatching on a node that can be one of several AST types**, favor **`Switch.type` / `switch_Exhaustive` / `Switch.bind` ** (from `@shared/TypeSafety.ts`, via the **`Switch`** object) together with **`ast.is<CollectionType>(node)`** where **`CollectionType`** is a Langium grammar type that is a **union** of exactly those alternatives.

That pattern gives **exhaustive handlers** (compile-time) and a **single** `ast.is<...>(node)` guard instead of long `if (ast.isA) ... else if (ast.isB) ...` chains.

## Prefer (exhaustive switch + union guard)

```typescript
import { Switch } from '@shared/TypeSafety'
import { AST } from '@parser'

if (ast.isTopLevelStatement(node)) {
  Switch.type(node, {
    UseStatement: (n) => { /* n is UseStatement */ },
    TopLevelDeclaration: (n) => { /* n is TopLevelDeclaration */ },
    Injection: (n) => { /* n is Injection */ },
  })
}
```

Grammar side: `TopLevelStatement` already groups `UseStatement | TopLevelDeclaration | Injection`, so `ast.isTopLevelStatement(node)` is the right collection guard.

## When if/else is OK

Use **`ast.is<SomeSingleNodeType>(node)`** only when You are checking **one** concrete type.

## When missing the needed `ast.is<UnionType>()`: extend the grammar

Add a **new type rule** in `tao-grammar.langium` that is a **union** of all node types you need. Then `./just-agents gen` to regenerate the AST.
